Scheduled tasks with cron.

Cron is the classic scheduler: it runs commands automatically at specified times. Each user gets their own cron table, usually shortened to crontab, which is simply a file listing scheduled jobs. You edit yours with crontab dash e, list it with crontab dash l, and remove it with crontab dash r, though take care, because that last one deletes it with no confirmation.

Each line in a crontab has six parts. The first five describe when to run, and the sixth is the command itself. Reading the time fields from left to right, they are: minute, hour, day of the month, month, and day of the week. So five numbers, then the command. Each of those time fields can be a single number, a range like nine through seventeen, a comma-separated list, a step such as every fifteen units, or a star meaning any value. With those building blocks you can express things like every fifteen minutes, daily at half past two in the morning, weekdays at nine, or the first of every month.

Cron has a few gotchas that trip up almost everyone, so commit them to memory. It runs your job with a minimal environment, where the search path is often just the bare system directories, so use full paths to your commands or set the path at the top of the crontab. It runs with no interactive shell, so anything that waits for input will simply hang forever. Its output is either emailed, if mail is configured, or silently lost, so redirect it explicitly to a log file. And always test the script by hand first, as the same user, because if it works in your shell but fails under cron, the cause is almost always that environment difference. Finally, note there are also system-wide crontabs under slash e-t-c, which add one extra field naming the user to run as, a field that your personal crontab does not need.
